<TEXT>
<P>
Speaking Up: Gennady I. Gerasimov, whose statements of "new thinking" in Soviet 
foreign policy made him a familiar figure on the world stage, will be presented 
the National Assn. of Government Communicators' "communicator of the year" 
award tonight in Washington, D.C. Gerasimov, 60, chief spokesman for the Soviet 
Foreign Ministry, is the first-ever foreign recipient of the award. 
</P>
<P>
Speaking Out: It was the not-so haunting theme from the old "Andy Griffith 
Show" that led police in Ft. Walton Beach, Fla., to Coco the stolen cockatiel 
and his alleged abductor, Frankie LaDel, 20. Coco was lifted Monday during a 
home burglary, along with $100 in change and $4,715 worth of camera gear, 
electronics equipment, jewelry, shoes and food. The next day, patrolman Jim 
Walker heard the unmistakable strains of the tune, punctuated by squawks, 
coming from a local tattoo parlor and remembered that the report on the 
birdnaping mentioned it was one of the bird's specialties. LaDel was located 
and arrested nearby. 
</P>
<P>
Speaking of Animals: Britain's Prince Philip stopped briefly at Orly Airport 
outside Paris Thursday to inaugurate an exposition of the World Wildlife Fund. 
The exhibit will be on view at Orly Airport until Jan. 15, during which time 
passengers at both Orly and at Charles de Gaulle Airport can place their coins 
into a transparent globe of the world held up by a model of a panda, the World 
Wildlife Fund's emblem. 
</P>
<P>
The Eyes Have It: Mademoiselle magazine looked into the eyes of some 
celebrities and learned quite a bit. A behavioral analyst says that Tom 
Cruise's left eye is bigger than the right one, showing a sense of 
spirituality, while Julia Roberts' long eyebrows mean she is artistic and 
independent. Warren Beatty's eyes reveal that he lacks commitment, and Anjelica 
Huston's powerful gaze says that she is straightforward while Meryl Streep's 
shows intelligence and dedication to family. Paul Newman's trademark blue eyes 
haven't faded, a sign of good health. 
</P>
</TEXT>
