<HEADLINE>
<P>
VENTURA COUNTY NEWS ROUNDUP: OXNARD; 
</P>
<P>
DREDGING NEAR HARBOR WILL HELP BEACHES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By KIRSTEN LEE SWARTZ 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
More than 1 million cubic feet of sand will be scooped from the ocean floor 
north of Channel Islands Harbor and piped to two county beaches as part of a 
periodic project to offset erosion, officials said. 
</P>
<P>
The dredge, pumping around the clock, will remove up to 2,000 cubic feet of 
sand an hour, spitting it out on Silver Strand Beach and areas south of Port 
Hueneme Beach, said Capt. Jack Peveler of the Channel Islands Harbor Police 
Department. 
</P>
<P>
"It's like a big water vacuum," he said. 
</P>
<P>
The Sand Bypass Project, expected to begin Wednesday and last until mid-March, 
will require boaters to radio harbor police before passing the 55-foot-wide, 
300-foot-long dredge, Peveler said. 
</P>
<P>
About 1.5 million cubic feet of sand will be removed from an area directly 
north of the harbor and the harbor's main entrance area. 
</P>
<P>
An additional 200,000 cubic feet will be removed from the entrance to Port 
Hueneme, he said. 
</P>
<P>
Western Pacific Dredging, a subsidiary of an Oregon-based company, will do the 
project for the Army Corps of Engineers and the Navy, he said. 
</P>
<P>
The equipment scoops the sand with a giant blade, sucks it up and pumps it to 
the beaches through pipes linked for more than a mile. 
</P>
<P>
Bulldozers will block areas of the beach to recondition the sand. 
</P>
<P>
"Until the sand settles, you could get stuck pretty bad," Peveler said. KIRSTEN 
LEE SWARTZ 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, A bulldozer, top, pulls a length of pipe onto Silver Strand Beach, which 
will be replenished with sand dredged from the ocean floor and pumped through 
the pipe. More pipes, above, lie on the beach south of Channel Islands Harbor 
in preparation for the project that is expected to begin next week and continue 
until mid-March. At left, a bulldozer is silhouetted amid tracks from 
pipe-moving equipment. LAWRENCE K. HO / Los Angeles Times; Photo, DREDGE PLANS: 
More than 1 million cubic feet of sand will be scooped from the ocean floor 
north of the Channel Islands Harbor and piped to two county beaches as part of 
a biannual project to offset erosion. 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
