<HEADLINE>
<P>
'DAVIS RULES' BUMPS 'CLASS' FROM ABC ROSTER 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By DIANE HAITHMAN 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABC put its struggling sitcom "Head of the Class" on indefinite hiatus Thursday 
to make room for another classroom comedy, "Davis Rules," starring Randy Quaid 
as an unconventional grammar school educator named Dwight Davis. 
</P>
<P>
"Davis Rules" will premiere Jan. 8 at 8:30 p.m. "Head of the Class" will have 
its last 1990 broadcast Dec. 28. 
</P>
<P>
"Davis Rules," the latest series from Carsey-Werner, also stars Jonathan 
Winters. 
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, NBC said Thursday that Bridget and Jerome Dobson, creators of "Santa 
Barbara," will return to the soap opera as head writers and creative production 
executives. 
</P>
<P>
The Dobsons were fired in September, 1987, after disputes over creative control 
with NBC and New World Television -- particularly over whether the Dobsons had 
the right to fire one of the show's staff writers. Lawsuits and counter-suits 
were filed. An NBC spokesman confirmed that those suits have since been settled 
out of court. 
</P>
<P>
John Conboy, hired as executive producer after the Dobsons' departure, will 
continue in that capacity. DIANE HAITHMAN 
</P>
</TEXT>
