<P>
P.M. BRIEFING; 
</P>
<P>
WIND NOISE FRAZZLES NEIGHBORS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Times Wire Services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
NEW YORK 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
As if life in the big city wasn't tough enough, neighbors living near a 
Manhattan skyscraper say a high-pitched whistle coming from it is driving them 
crazy. 
</P>
<P>
"I've been all over the street trying to follow the noise," said Anthony 
Mazzola, who lives about a block away from the 72-story Cityspire. 
</P>
<P>
"You think you're in a loony bin. You can't get away from it." 
</P>
<P>
Department of Environmental Protection inspectors blame wind blowing over 
louvers on the mid-town building's green, eight-sided dome, which is about 800 
feet above the ground, for the noise. 
</P>
<P>
At its worst, the whistle can be heard 10 blocks away, although its intensity 
depends on wind conditions, said Jerome Ross, an environmental protection 
enforcement officer. 
</P>
<P>
The building's developer, Ian Bruce Eichner, has been issued a summons for 
allegedly violating noise regulations, Ross said. If found guilty, Eichner 
would have to mute the whistling and pay a fine of up to $880, Ross said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
